03980nam a22006375i 9780823296842DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20211993nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232968427 a10.1515/97808232968422doi  a(DE-B1597)575273  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLCO0100002bisacsh1 aBurton, David H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Holmes-Sheehan Correspondence :bThe Letters of Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr. and Canon Patrick Augustine Sheehan /cDavid H. Burton. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (96 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe letters -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOliver Wendell Holmes, Jr., distinguished American jurist, and Patrick Augustine Sheehan, an Irish clerical-savant, enjoyed a warm and notable friendship based largely on their exchange of letters from 1903, when they first met in Ireland, until 1913, the year of Sheehan's death. This correspondence illuminates what is otherwise a largely hidden and little appreciated side of the mind and faith of Justince Holmes. Sheehan was able to draw from his friend an awareness and sympathy for human frailty and its counterpoint, faith in a divine plan of earthly things, thoughts and feelings that surfaced in letters to other of his friends. The importance of this edition of the Holmes-Sheehan letters rests in the first instance on this discovery. But Canon Sheehan wsa no mere foil for Holmes as they discussed with equal insight issues as varied as the economic man and the age of faith, of classical works, including Dante's Divine Comedy and Pascal's Pensees. Holmes discovered in the Canon a man of the most profound faith who remained open and tolerant of the beliefs and non-beliefs of others. He is better understood because of his affection for Sheehan, and, no less telling, because of the Canon's admiration for him. Gary J. Aichele in Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.: Soldier, Scholar, Judge finds this set of letters "perhaps the most unusual" of any collection of Holmes correspondence published to date.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831107432960 cprintz978082321525640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329684240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296842/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK